View of Bow Lake and Crowfoot Glacier in Banff National Park with a man in front of a tipi in the foreground.
This view of Bow Lake is one of the most famous and best loved images in the Byron Harmon collection. It is a clear example of Byron's ability to envision and create a scene. The teepee is pitched on a marshy promontory which projects into the lake, one would never camp in this location. A local tale claims that the photograph was so popular that other photographers in later years pitched a teepee in the same place each summer for visitors to photograph.

